      <p class="hero-label">Diagrams as text</p>
      <h1>Mermaid and Markdown</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Mermaid is a text-based diagramming language that lives inside a Markdown fenced code block. Write a few lines of plain text, get a flowchart, a sequence diagram, or a Gantt chart in return. No drawing tool. No image files. No diagrams that go stale.</p>
      <p class="hero-ingress">The connection between Mermaid and Markdown is not accidental — it is philosophical. Both are built on the idea that structure should be legible in plain text, not locked in a proprietary format. A Mermaid diagram is readable as source. It lives in the same file as the prose around it. It can be reviewed in a pull request, searched with grep, and versioned with git. GitHub renders it automatically. So does GitLab, Notion, and Obsidian. The diagram is the documentation, in the same way Markdown made the source the document.</p>
